# DRONE.md — Project Knowledge

> Drop this file at your project root (or `.drone/DRONE.md`) and DevClaw will
> auto-inject it into every task's system prompt.
>
> Keep it tight: think of it as a one-page onboarding doc for a new contractor
> who needs to ship code today.

## Project conventions

- Language and version (e.g. Go 1.24, Node 20, Python 3.12)
- Module path / package name
- Test command (e.g. `go test ./...`, `npm test`, `pytest`)
- Lint / format command
- Code style notes (e.g. gofmt, no global mutable state, kebab-case file names)

## Architecture

Briefly describe each top-level directory and its role.

```
.
├── cmd/        Application entry points
├── internal/   Private business logic
├── pkg/        Exported helpers
└── docs/       Reference docs
```

## Forbidden / sensitive areas

- Files DevClaw must not edit (e.g. `LICENSE`, `CHANGELOG.md`, generated code)
- Secrets that must never be logged
- API endpoints that must not be removed without coordination

## Common tasks the agent should do well

- Add a new HTTP endpoint: handler in `internal/api/`, register in `cmd/server`
- Add a new database migration: `migrations/NNNN_*.sql`, run `make migrate`
- Add a new feature flag: define in `pkg/config`, default off, doc'd in CHANGELOG
